This paper is likely to belong to the Computer Vision (cs.CV) sub-category as it proposes a new architecture to improve classification accuracy of Deep Convolutional Networks (DCN) on a popular dataset. Additionally, the paper also suggests sharing low-level convolutional layers between experts to avoid computation of a near-duplicate feature set, which is a common technique used in computer vision. 

The paper also falls under the sub-category of Machine Learning (cs.LG) as it proposes a supervised architecture that uses expert networks to improve classification accuracy. 

The paper may also belong to the Artificial Intelligence (cs.AI) sub-category as it proposes a new architecture that allows for incremental learning, which is a common topic in AI research. 

The Neural and Evolutionary Computing (cs.NE) sub-category is also a possibility as the paper proposes a new architecture that uses multiple experts to improve classification accuracy, which is a common technique used in neural networks. 

Finally, the Computational Linguistics (cs.CL) sub-category is a possibility as the paper proposes a new architecture that uses a mediator to resolve conflicts between experts, which is a technique commonly used in natural language processing.
